# ✅ Example 3: Using Cookies for Auth (SAFE WAY)

### ✅ Rule

*   React **SHOULD NOT read auth cookies**
*   Backend sets **HttpOnly cookies**
*   React only sends requests

***

## ✅ Server sets cookie

```http
Set-Cookie: refreshToken=abc123; HttpOnly; SameSite=Lax
```

***

## ✅ React sends request (cookie auto‑attached)

```jsx
fetch("http://localhost:4000/refresh", {
  method: "POST",
  credentials: "include" // VERY IMPORTANT
});
```

✅ React **cannot read** the cookie  
✅ Browser handles it securely

***

# ❌ Example 4: What NOT to Do (Very Important)

```jsx
// ❌ NEVER store auth tokens like this
Cookies.set("token", jwtToken);
localStorage.setItem("token", jwtToken);
```

Why ❌?

*   Vulnerable to XSS
*   Tokens can be stolen

✅ Auth tokens must be **HttpOnly cookies**

***

# ✅ When Should React Use Cookies?

| Scenario         | Use Cookie?       |
| ---------------- | ----------------- |
| Theme            | ✅ Yes             |
| Language         | ✅ Yes             |
| User preferences | ✅ Yes             |
| JWT / Auth token | ❌ No              |
| Refresh token    | ✅ (HttpOnly only) |

***

# ✅ Cookies vs React State

| Feature          | React State | Cookie |
| ---------------- | ----------- | ------ |
| Survives refresh | ❌           | ✅      |
| Survives new tab | ❌           | ✅      |
| Security         | ✅           | ⚠️     |
| Server access    | ❌           | ✅      |

✅ Often used **together**

***

# ✅ Interview‑Ready Summary (MEMORIZE)

✅ React uses cookies via JS or libraries  
✅ Cookies persist across refresh & tabs  
✅ `js-cookie` is preferred  
✅ React cannot read HttpOnly cookies  
✅ Auth cookies are server‑controlled  
✅ Cookies + React state = best UX

